  "nursesNote": "The nurse protects psychiatric patients' rights. Voluntary patients admit themselves and may request discharge (though a brief evaluation may delay release if they become a danger). Involuntary (committed) patients are admitted against their will because they are a danger to self or others or are gravely disabled. Importantly, committed patients keep their rights, including dignity, communication, confidentiality, informed consent, and usually the right to refuse medication, unless there is an emergency or a court order. Care uses the least restrictive option, with seclusion or restraint only as a last resort. Confidentiality is protected, with a key exception: the duty to warn an identifiable person whom the patient has seriously threatened. In an emergency, the nurse may treat to prevent imminent harm and then document. The nurse advocates for patients and reports any rights violations.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Distinguish voluntary from involuntary status",
    "Ensure committed patients keep their rights",
    "Honor the right to refuse treatment unless an emergency or court order applies",
    "Use the least restrictive care option",
    "Maintain confidentiality but follow the duty to warn"
  ],
